A Boettcher cell is a polyhedral cells on the basilar membrane of the cochlea, and is located beneath Claudius cells. A Boettcher cell is considered a supporting cell for the organ of Corti, and is present only in the lower turn of the cochlea. These cells interweave with each other, and project microvilli into the intercellular space. Because of their structural specialization, a Boettcher cell is believed to play a significant role in the function of the cochlea. They demonstrate high levels of calmodulin, and may be involved in mediating Ca(2+) regulation and ion transport.

Specialized elongated ventricular ependymal cell that has processes that extend to the outer, or pial, surface of the CNS. Resemble spongioblasts seen in developing brain. Found in the adult brain in the third ventricle, cerebral aqueduct, spinal canal and floor of the fourth ventricle.
A cardiac myocyte that is an excitable cells in the myocardium, specifically in the conducting system of heart.
A leukocyte that lacks granules.

comments: Some argue this cell type is of mesenchymal origin.

definition.val: This is a cell found in the gastrointestinal tract of mammals and serves as a pacemaker that triggers gut contraction. ICCs mediate inputs from the enteric nervous system to smooth muscle cells and are thought to be the cells from which gastrointestinal stromal tumors (GISTs) arise.

A group 2 innate lymphoid cell in the mouse capable of secreting IL-13 in response to a helminth infection. This cell is lineage-negative, ICOS-positive, IL1RL1-positive, IL7Ralpha-positive, and IL17Br-positive.
One of two small cells formed by the first and second meiotic division of oocytes.
A small cell formed by the first meiotic division of oocytes.

comments: MH consider whether bone marrow cells are bone cells in the structural sense vs. being part of bone organ sense.

definition.val: A cell found in the bone marrow. This can include fibroblasts, macrophages, adipocytes, osteoblasts, osteoclasts, endothelial cells and hematopoietic cells.
A small cell formed by the second meiotic division of oocytes. In mammals, the second polar body may fail to form unless the ovum has been penetrated by a sperm cell.
A cell that makes up the loose connective tissue of the ovary.
A cell in the hilum of the ovary that produces androgens.
A specialised myocyte that lies between the sinoatrial node and the atrioventricular node and is involved in the conduction of electrical signals.
A cell of the adrenal cortex. Cell types include those that synthesize and secrete chemical derivatives (steroids) of cholesterol.
A cardiac myocyte that is connected to other cardiac myocytes by transverse intercalated discs (GO:0014704) at a regular interval.

nodes.lbl: type I cell of adrenal cortex

definition.val: A small, polyhedral, cell found in rounded groups or curved columns with deeply staining nuclei, scanty basophilic cytoplasm and a few lipid droplets. This cell in the zona glomerulosa produces mineralocorticoids.

synonyms.val: epithelial cell of zona glomerulosa of adrenal gland

definition.val: A regular cardiac myocyte of the interventricular region of the heart.

A CD38-positive naive B cell is a mature B cell that has the phenotype CD38-positive, surface IgD-positive, surface IgM-positive, and CD27-negative, and that has not yet been activated by antigen in the periphery.

A CD38-negative naive B cell is a mature B cell that has the phenotype CD38-negative, surface IgD-positive, surface IgM-positive, and CD27-negative, that has not yet been activated by antigen in the periphery.

nodes.lbl: IgG-positive double negative memory B cell

definition.val: An IgG-positive double negative memory B cell is a double negative memory B cell with the phenotype IgG-positive, IgD-negative, and CD27-negative.

synonyms.val: IgG+ double negative memory B cell
IgG+ double negative memory B lymphocyte
IgG-positive double negative memory B lymphocyte

nodes.lbl: IgG-negative double negative memory B cell

definition.val: An IgG-negative double negative memory B cell is a double negative memory B cell with the phenotype IgG-negative, IgD-negative, and CD27-negative.

synonyms.val: IgG- double negative memory B cell
IgG- double negative memory B lymphocyte
IgG-negative double negative memory B lymphocyte

definition.val: A CD38-positive IgG memory B cell is a class switched memory B cell that expresses IgG on the cell surface with the phenotype CD38-positive and IgG-positive.

nodes.lbl: IgD-positive CD38-positive IgG memory B cell

definition.val: An IgD-positive CD38-positive IgG memory B cell is a CD38-positive IgG-positive class switched memory B cell that has class switched and expresses IgD on the cell surface with the phenotype IgD-positive, CD38-positive, and IgG-positive.

nodes.lbl: IgD-negative CD38-positive IgG memory B cell

definition.val: An IgD-negative CD38-positive IgG memory B cell is a CD38-positive IgG-positive that has class switched and lacks expression of IgD on the cell surface with the phenotype IgD-negative, CD38-positive, and IgG-positive.

A CD38-negative IgG memory B cell is a IgG-positive class switched memory B cell that has class switched and expresses IgG on the cell surface with the phenotype CD38-negative, IgD-negative, and IgG-positive.

A B220-positive CD38-positive naive B cell is a CD38-positive naive B cell that has the phenotype B220-positive, CD38-positive, surface IgD-positive, surface IgM-positive, and CD27-negative, and that has not yet been activated by antigen in the periphery.

A B220-low CD38-positive naive B cell is a CD38-positive naive B cell that has the phenotype B220-low, CD38-positive, surface IgD-positive, surface IgM-positive, and CD27-negative, that has not yet been activated by antigen in the periphery.
An CD38-negative unswitched memory B cell is an unswitched memory B cell that has the phenotype CD38-negative, IgD-positive, CD138-negative, and IgG-negative.

nodes.lbl: B220-positive CD38-negative unswitched memory B cell

definition.val: A B220-positive CD38-negative unswitched memory B cell is a CD38-negative unswitched memory B cell that has the phenotype B220-positive, CD38-negative, IgD-positive, CD138-negative, and IgG-negative.

nodes.lbl: B220-low CD38-negative unswitched memory B cell

definition.val: A B220-low CD38-negative unswitched memory B cell is a CD38-negative unswitched memory B cell that has the phenotype B220-low, CD38-negative, IgD-positive, CD138-negative, and IgG-negative.
A CD38-positive unswitched memory B cell is an unswitched memory B cell that has the phenotype CD38-positive, IgD-positive, CD138-negative, and IgG-negative.

nodes.lbl: B220-positive CD38-positive unswitched memory B cell

definition.val: A B220-positive CD38-positive unswitched memory B cell is a CD38-positive unswitched memory B cell that has the phenotype B220-positive, CD38-positive, IgD-positive, CD138-negative, and IgG-negative.

nodes.lbl: B220-low CD38-positive unswitched memory B cell

definition.val: A B220-low CD38-positive unswitched memory B cell is a CD38-positive unswitched memory B cell that has the phenotype B220-low, CD38-positive, IgD-positive, CD138-negative, and IgG-negative.

nodes.lbl: IgG-negative class switched memory B cell

definition.val: A class switched memory B cell that lacks IgG on the cell surface.

synonyms.val: IgG- class switched memory B cell
IgG- class switched memory B lymphocyte
IgG-negative class switched memory B lymphocyte

nodes.lbl: CD38-negative IgG-negative class switched memory B cell

definition.val: A CD38-negative IgG-negative memory B cell is a IgG-negative class switched memory B cell that lacks IgG on the cell surface with the phenotype CD38-negative and IgG-negative.

nodes.lbl: CD38-positive IgG-negative class switched memory B cell

definition.val: A CD38-positive IgG-negative memory B cell is an IgG-negative class switched memory B cell that lacks IgG on the cell surface with the phenotype CD38-positive and IgG-negative.

nodes.lbl: CD24-positive CD38-negative IgG-negative class switched memory B cell

definition.val: An CD24-positive CD38-negative IgG-negative memory B cell is a CD38-negative IgG-negative class switched memory B cell that lacks IgG on the cell surface with the phenotype CD24-positive, CD38-negative, and IgG-negative.

nodes.lbl: CD24-negative CD38-negative IgG-negative class switched memory B cell

definition.val: A CD24-negative CD38-negative IgG-negative memory B cell is a CD38-negative IgG-negative class switched memory B cell that lacks IgG on the cell surface with the phenotype CD24-negative, CD38-negative, and IgG-negative.

nodes.lbl: B220-positive CD38-positive IgG-negative class switched memory B cell

definition.val: A B220-positive CD38-positive IgG-negative memory B cell is a CD38-positive IgG-negative class switched memory B cell that lacks IgG on the cell surface with the phenotype B220-positive, CD38-positive, and IgG-negative.

nodes.lbl: B220-low CD38-positive IgG-negative class switched memory B cell

definition.val: A B220-low CD38-positive IgG-negative memory B cell is a CD38-positive IgG-negative class switched memory B cell that lacks IgG on the cell surface with the phenotype B220-low, CD38-positive, and IgG-positive.
A circulating gamma-delta T cell that is CD27-positive and capable of producing IFN-gamma.
A circulating gamma-delta T cell that expresses RORgamma(t), is CD27-negative and is capable of IL-17 secretion.

nodes.lbl: CD25-positive, CD27-positive immature gamma-delta T cell

definition.val: A CD25-positive, CD27-positive immature gamma-delta T cell found in the thymus that has an immature phenotype (i.e. CD24-high, CD25-high, CD62L-high, CD44-high, CD2-low, CD5-low).
A T cell with a receptor of limited diversity that is capable of immediate effector functions upon stimulation.

comments: This cell type is compatible with the HIPC Lyoplate markers for 'Tc17 CD8+ T cell', but its logical definition includes additional known characteristics of Tc17 T cells.  Found in the CD27-positive, CD28-positive or CD27-negative, CD28-positive fractions with the phenotype CCR4-negative and CCR7-negative (this sentence not part of definition).

definition.val: A CD8-positive, alpha-beta T cell that has the phenotype CXCR3-negative, CCR6-positive, CCR5-high, CD45RA-negative, and capable of producing IL-17 and some IFNg.
Regular cardiac myocyte of a cardiac atrium.

synonyms.val: regular cardiac muscle cell of atrium

definition.val: A cardiac myocyte of the interatrial region of the heart.
Regular cardiac myocyte of a cardiac ventricle.

synonyms.val: regular cardiac muscle cell of ventricle

definition.val: A stomal cell of the ovary
A stromal cell of the ovarian cortex.
A stromal cell of the ovarian medulla.
Epidermal cells that do not contain keratin. Cell type is usually associated with moist epidermal tissues.

nodes.lbl: type II cell of adrenal cortex

definition.val: A cell in the zona fasciculata that produce glucocorticoids, e.g cortisol.

synonyms.val: type II cortical cell of adrenal gland

nodes.lbl: type III cell of adrenal cortex

definition.val: A cell in the zona reticularis that produce sex hormones.

A endothelial cell of a lymphatic vessel. The border of the oak leaf-shaped endothelial cell of initial lymphatics are joined by specialized buttons. The discontinuous feature of buttons distinguishes them from zippers in collecting lymphatics, but both types of junctions are composed of proteins typical of adherens junctions and tight junctions found in the endothelium of blood vessels. Buttons seal the sides of flaps of the oak leaf-shaped endothelial cell, leaving open the tips of flaps as routes for fluid entry without disassembly and reformation of intercellular junctions.

comments: These cells are reportedly CD31-positive, CD34-positive, CD144-positive, TAL1-positive.

definition.val: An endothelial cell of the vascular tree, which includes blood vessels and lymphatic vessels.

synonyms.val: cubodial endothelial cell of vascular tree

definition.val: A sebum secreting cell of the skin that secretes sebum into the hair follicles.

nodes.lbl: active chief cell of parathyroid gland

definition.val: A parathyroid chief cell that is actively secreting hormone. Have large Golgi complexes with numerous vesicles and small membrane-bound granules; secretory granules are rare, cytoplasmic glycogen sparse, much of the cytoplasm being occupied by flat sacs of granular endoplasmic reticulum in parallel arrays; in normal humans, inactive chief cells outnumber active chief cells in a ratio of 3-5:1

nodes.lbl: dark cell of eccrine sweat gland

definition.val: A cell pyramidal in shape, with their broad ends facing and forming the greater extent of the lining of the main lumen. Secretes glycoproteins associated with mucus.

nodes.lbl: dark chief cell of parathyroid gland

definition.val: A chief cell that is smaller than light chief cells and has a smaller and darker nucleus and a finely granular cytoplasm with many granules.
An endothelial cell found in capillaries.

nodes.lbl: ciliated columnar cell of tracheobronchial tree

definition.val: A ciliated columnar cell found in the trachea and bronchus. Vary from low to tall columnar; possesses up to 300 cilia at its surface, interspersed with long irregular microvilli with the cilia varying in length from about 6um in the trachea to about 4um in the terminal bronchioles; driving force of the ciliary current in the bronchial tree.

nodes.lbl: clear cell of eccrine sweat gland

definition.val: A sweat producing cell of eccrine sweat glands. Pyramidal in shape, with its base resting on the basal lamina or myoepitheliocytes, and its microvillus-covered apical plasma membrane line up the intercellular canaliculi. Cell is not stained by hematoxylin or eosin.

nodes.lbl: clear chief cell of parathyroid gland

definition.val: A chief cell of parathyroid glands that does not stain with hematoxylin or eosin. This cell is larger, has a larger nucleus and fewer secretory granules than dark chief cells.

synonyms.val: clear chief cell of parathyroid cell

definition.val: A cell found within the dental pulp.
An epithelial cell of the uterus.

Epithelioid macrophage is an activated macrophage that resembles an epithelial cell with finely granular, pale eosinophilic cytoplasm and central, ovoid nucleus (oval or elongate). This cell type is able to merge into one another to form aggregates. The presence of such aggregates may characterize some pathologic conditions, mainly granulomatous inflammation.
A promyelocyte that is considerably smaller, with more condensed chromatin, and nucleoli are no longer conspicuous.
A columnar cell of the cervix uteri.
The dead keratin-filled squamous cell of the stratum corneum. This cell type lacks a nucleus.

A promyelocyte with a nucleus that is indented and contains more marginated heterochromatin compared to its precursor cell (myeloblast); cytoplasm is deeply basophilic and contains numerous mitochondria and meandering cysternae of endoplasmic reticulum; largest of the granulocyte lineages.
A crenated erythrocyte with 30+ crenations, bumps or spurs that are the result of damage due to age or disease.
A cell type that makes up the highly vascular membrane lining the marrow cavity of long bones.

nodes.lbl: external epithelial cell of tympanic membrane

definition.val: Epithelial cell found on the external side of the tympanic membrane
Epithelial cells derived from general body ectoderm and ectoderm placodes.

nodes.lbl: basal external epithelial cell of tympanic membrane

definition.val: A cell type found in the basal epithelial layer on the external side of the tympanic membrane. Cell type is flattened with intracellular spaces of variable dimensions.

nodes.lbl: superficial external epithelial cell of tympanic membrane

definition.val: A cell type found on the superficial layer of the external side of the tympanic membrane. This cell-type lacks a nucleus.

nodes.lbl: internal epithelial cell of tympanic membrane

definition.val: An extremely flattened cell type found on the inner side of the tympanic membrane. The surface of this cell type carries sparse pleomorphic microvilli that are more common near the junctional zones.
A rod-shpaed cell that forms a single row adjacent to and supporting the inner hair cells.
A rod-shaped cell found in 3 or 4 rows that lie adjacent to and support the outer hair cells.
A supporting cell that is attached to the basement membrane and forms rows that support the hair cells.
An epithelial cell that remains from the disintegration of the epithelial root sheath involved in the development of teeth.
A specialized cell involved in sensory perception of smell.
A border cell is a slender columnar cell on the medial portion of the basilar membrane.
An epithelial cell located on the basal lamina of the olfactory epithelium.

nodes.lbl: keratinized cell of the oral mucosa

definition.val: A keratinized cell located in the hard palate or gingiva.

A rounded or elliptical epithelial cell, with pale-staining open face nucleus and pale cytoplasm rich in free ribosomes and clusters of centrioles; form a distinct basal zone spaced slightly from the basal surface of the epithelium.
A long, spindle-shaped supporting cells arranged in parallel rows that secretes components of the tectorial membrane and potassium ions into the endolymph.

A cell that is a specialized type of pericyte providing structural support for the capillary loops of kidney. A flat, elongated cell with extensive fine cytoplasmic processes found outside the kidney glomerulus near the macula densa and bound laterally by afferent and efferent arterioles. Being phagocytic, this cell participates in the continuous turnover of the basal lamina by removing its outer portion containing residues of filtration, while the lamina is renewed on its inner surface by the endothelial cells.
A cell within the follicle of an ovary.
A cell within the primary follicle of the ovary.
A cell of a secondary follicile within the ovary.

nodes.lbl: folliculostellate cell of pars distalis of adenohypophysis

definition.val: A supporting cell of the anterior pituitary gland involved in trophic and catabolic processes; expresses a broad spectrum of cytokeratins indicative of their epithelial nature.

synonyms.val: folliculostellate cell of pars anterior of adenohypophysis

definition.val: An epithelial cell found in the lining of the stomach.
An epithelial cell within one of the pits in the embryonic gastric mucosa from which the gastric glands develop .
A mucous cell in the epithelium of the stomach.

nodes.lbl: mucus neck cell of gastric gland

definition.val: A neck cell that secretes mucus within the stomach. Its products are distinct histochemically from those of the surface mucous cells of stomach.
A simple columnar cell that populates the entire luminal surface including the gastric pits. This cell types secrete mucus to form a thick protective, lubricant layer over the gastric wall.

A stomach epithelial cell that is olumnar in form with a few short apical microvilli; relatively undifferentiated mitotic cell from which other types of gland are derived; few in number, situated in the isthmus region of the gland and base of the gastric pit.

nodes.lbl: basal proper cell of olfactory epithelium

definition.val: A flat or angular epithelial cell with condensed nuclei and darkly staining cytoplasm containing numerous intermediate filaments inserted into desmosomes contacting surrounding supporting cells; lie in contact with the basal lamina of olfactory epithelium.
A basally situated, mitotically active, columnar-shaped keratinocyte attached to the basement membrane.
An endothelial cell found in the glomerulus of the kidney. This cell is flattened, highly fenestrated, and plays a vital role in the formation of glomerular ultrafiltrate.
A keratinocyte of the epidermis that is characterized by containing granules of keratohyalin and lamellar granules.
A flat keratinocyte immediately below the cornified layer.
A cell involved in the formation of a granulocyte.

A eosinophil precursor in the granulocytic series, being a cell intermediate in development between a myelocyte and a band form cell. The nucleus becomes indented where the indentation is smaller than half the distance to the farthest nuclear margin; chromatin becomes coarse and clumped; specific granules predominate while primary granules are rare.

A cell type that is the first of the maturation stages of the granulocytic leukocytes normally found in the bone marrow. Granules are seen in the cytoplasm. The nuclear material of the myelocyte is denser than that of the myeloblast but lacks a definable membrane. The cell is flat and contains increasing numbers of granules as maturation progresses.
A cell involved in the formation of a monocyte (monopoiesis).
A stem cell that can give rise to the cells of the liver.
A transient hepatic stem cell observed after liver injury with a high nuclear to cytoplasm ratio that can differentiate into mature hepatocytes and bile duct cells. Arises from more than one tissue.

nodes.lbl: inactive chief cell of parathyoid gland

definition.val: A parathyroid chief cell that is not actively secreting hormone. Contains small Golgi complexes with only a few grouped vesicles and membrane-bound secretory granules; glycogen and many lipofuscin granules abound but sacs of granular endoplasmic reticulum are rare and dispersed. In normal humans, inactive chief cells out number active chief cells in a ratio of 3-5:1.

A large epithelial cell with an extremely acidophilic and granular cytoplasm, containing vast numbers of mitochondria; such cells may undergo neoplastic transformation. From the Greek word onkos meaning swelling, this cell type is found in parathyroid, salivary and thyroid glands.
An oncocyte located in the parathyroid gland.
An oncocyte located in the thyroid.
A renal intercalated cell that secretes base and reabsorbs acid in the coritcal collecting duct to mantain acid/base balance.
An epithelial cell of the tracheobronchial tree.

nodes.lbl: brush cell of epithelium proper of large intestine

comments: Brush cells are a distinct cell type from brush border cell-types.

definition.val: Brush cell found in the epithelial layer of the colon.

synonyms.val: tuft cell of epithelium of large intestine

definition.val: A cell type found in the gastrointestinal and respiratory tracts that is characterized by the presence of a tuft of blunt, squat microvilli (120-140 per cell). Function of this cell type is not known.
A brush cell found in the epithelium of lobular bronchiole.
A brush cell of the epithelium in the terminal bronchiole.
Brush cell of the epithelium in the trachea.
A brush cell found in the epithelium of bronchus.
An epithelial cell present in the trachea and bronchi; columnar in shape; generally lack cilia; immature forms of ciliated or secretory cells which have been formed from stem cells.

synonyms.val: undifferentiated columnar cell of tracheobronchial tree

definition.val: A slow muscle cell that contains high levels of myoglobin and oxygen storing proteins giving the cell a red appearance.
A slow muscle cell that has large amounts of myoglobin, stores energy as triglycerides, generates ATP by the oxidative method and is resistant to fatigue.
A fast muscle fiber cell that stores energy in the form of glycogen and creatine phosphate.
A muscle cell with low content of myoglobin and other oxygen storing proteins. This muscle cell has a white appearance.

A type II muscle cell that contains large amounts of myoglobin, has many mitochondria and very many blood capillaries. Type II A cells are red, have a very high capacity for generating ATP by oxidative metabolic processes, split ATP at a very rapid rate, have a fast contraction velocity and are resistant to fatigue.

synonyms.val: fatigue resistant fast twitch muscle cell

definition.val: A type II muscle cell that contains a low content of myoglobin, relatively few mitochondria, relatively few blood capillaries and large amounts of glycogen. Type II B fibres are white, geared to generate ATP by anaerobic metabolic processes, not able to supply skeletal muscle fibres continuously with sufficient ATP, fatigue easily, split ATP at a fast rate and have a fast contraction velocity.
An intermediate muscle cell that has characteristics of both fast and slow muscle cells.
A trophoblast that leaves the placenta and invades the endometrium and myometrium. This cell type is crucial in increasing blood flow to the fetus.

nodes.lbl: immature dendritic epithelial T cell precursor

comments: NOTE: currently variable immune gene segments are not represented in the OBO Foundry. Cross-product definitions were not made as a result. Also, there are three different nomenclatures for the variable gamma segments.

definition.val: A double negative thymocyte that has a T cell receptor consisting of a gamma chain that has as part a Vgamma3 segment, and a delta chain. This cell type is CD4-negative, CD8-negative and CD24-positive. This cell-type is found in the fetal thymus with highest numbers occurring at E17-E18.

A trophoblast found at the junction of the placenta. This cell type makes a unique fibronectin-trophouteronectin junction that helps mediate attachment of the placenta to the uterus. This cell type is also found junction of the chorion layer of the external membranes and the decidua.
A cell located between the pinealocytes.
A squamous cell that has keratin in the esophagus.
A cell comprising the transparent, biconvex body separating the posterior chamber and vitreous body, and constituting part of the refracting mechanism of the mammalian eye.
A cell of the transparent layer of simple cuboidal epithelium over the anterior surface of the lens; transform into lens fiber(s).

A cell of the cuboidal epithelium that covers the lens. The cells of the lens epithelium regulate most of the homeostatic functions of the lens. As ions, nutrients, and liquid enter the lens from the aqueous humor, Na+/K+ ATPase pumps in the lens epithelial cells pump ions out of the lens to maintain appropriate lens osmolarity and volume, with equatorially positioned lens epithelium cells contributing most to this current. The activity of the Na+/K+ ATPases keeps water and current flowing through the lens from the poles and exiting through the equatorial regions. The cells of the lens epithelium also serve as the progenitors for new lens fibers. It constantly lays down fibers in the embryo, fetus, infant, and adult, and continues to lay down fibers for lifelong growth.
A lens fiber cell that develops from primary lens fiber; located towards the center of lens; cell organelles are normally degraded or in the process of being degraded.
A secondary lens fiber cell that lacks a nucleus.
A secondary fiber cell that contains a nucleus.

An elongating cell that rapidly obliterates the lumen of the lens vesicle. Subsequently, differentiation of this cell type at the lens equator leads to the formation of secondary fiber cells that come to overlie the primary fibers.

nodes.lbl: light chief cell of parathyroid gland

definition.val: A chief cell that is bigger than dark chief cells and has a larger and lighter nucleus and a cytoplasm with few granules.
An epithelial cell of the prostate.
An epithelial cell of prostatic duct.
An epithelial cell of the prostatic acinus.
A cell of the basal layer of the epithelium in the prostatic acinus.

synonyms.val: basal epithelial cell of prostatic acinus

definition.val: A cell of the luminal layer of the epithelium in the prostatic acinus.

nodes.lbl: basal epithelial cell of prostatic duct

definition.val: A cell that constitutes the basal layer of epithelium in the prostatic duct.

nodes.lbl: luminal epithelial cell of prostatic duct

definition.val: A cell that constitutes the luminal layer of epithelium of prostatic duct.
A primordial germ cell that is destined to become a male germ cell.
A primordial cell from which an oocyte (ovum) ultimately is developed.
A fibroblast in the bone marrow.
A fibroblasts found in interstitial spaces in the pulmonary tract. Greater numbers of these cells are found in idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis.
A cell containing at least one nucleus.

nodes.lbl: smooth muscle cell of sphincter of pupil

definition.val: A circular smooth muscle cell of the iris, innervated by the ciliary nerves (parasympathetic), and acting to contract the pupil. This muscle cell derives from neuroectoderm. This smooth muscle cell results from transformation of epithelial cells to smooth muscle cells.

synonyms.val: smooth muscle fiber of sphincter of pupil
smooth muscle fibre of sphincter of pupil

definition.val: A nonstratified squamous cell located in the ectocervix.
OBSOLETE: A lymphocyte that lacks T or B cell surface markers.
A hematopoeitic stem cell found in the blood. Normally found in very limited numbers in the peripheral circulation (less than 0.1% of all nucleated cells).
A tissue macrophage that is in the pleural space.

A pluripotent stem cell has the ability to form cells from all three germ layers (ectoderm, mesoderm, and endoderm). However, unlike totipotent stem cells, they cell can not generate all the cells of the whole organism such as placenta.
A stem cell that can differentiate into a cardiac myocyte.

A cell that is found in a zone occupying the bottom region of the crypt; provide the source of most of the cell types of the intestinal epithelium; proliferate by mitotic division; differentiates into columnar or goblet cells.

synonyms.val: stem cell of intestinal crypt of Lieberkuhn

definition.val: An epithelial cell of the musculomembranous digestive tube extending from the mouth to the anus.
An epithelial cell of the esophagus.
An epithelial cell of the large intestine.
An epithelial cell of the small intestine.

Connective tissue cells of the endometrium, these cells are fibroblastic in appearance. During decidualization they tranform into decidual (stromal) cells, swellling up and adopt an epithelial cell-like appearance due to the accumulation of glycogen and lipid droplets.
A supportive cell that has characteristics of glial cell. Processes of this cell envelope the junctions between glomus cells and nerve endings.
An epithelial cell of thyroid gland.
A cell type that varies from squamous to columnar, depending on their activity with microvillus directed luminally. This cell produces and secretes thyroid hormones.
The stem cell from which glial precursor cell arises from.
An epithelial cell of the parathyroid gland.
An endothelial cell found in the mucosa associated with the facial skeleton.
An endothelial cell that lines any of the venous cavities through which blood passes in various glands and organs such as the spleen and liver.

One of three types of epithelial cells that populate the parathyroid gland; cytological characteristics intermediate between those of the chief cell and of the oxyphil cell. Because only one hormone is produced, the three cell forms are widely believed to be different phases in the life cycle of a single cell type, with the chief cell being its physiologically active stage.
A type of enteroendocrine cell found in the stomach that secretes glucagon.
A D cell located in the colon.

nodes.lbl: type D cell of small intestine

definition.val: A type D cell of the small intestine.
A type D cell found in the stomach.
An enteroendocrine cell that stores and secretes Ghrelin.
An endocrine cell that secretes vasoactive intestinal peptide.
A type EC enteroendocrine cell in the duodenum and jejunum that stores and secretes motilin and 5-hydroxytryptamine.
A type EC enteredocrine cell in the intestines that stores and secretes substance P and 5-hydroxytryptamine.
A cell that secretes motilin, a gastric hormone that at low pH inhibits gastric motor activity, whereas at high pH has a stimulating effect.
A type EC enteroendocrine cell type that is numerous in the fundus of the stomach; stores 5-hydroxytryptamine and histamine.
A cell type that secretes histamine.

comments: The term PP cell of pancreatic acinus was obsoleted due to a lack of evidence, making PP cell of pancreatic islets synonymous with pancreatic PP cell.

definition.val: A PP cell located in the islets of the pancreas.

nodes.lbl: obsolete PP cell of pancreatic acinus

definition.val: OBSOLETE: A PP cell located in the pancreatic acinus. Obsoleted due to a lack of published evidence that this cell type is actually found in the pancreatic acinus.

synonyms.val: type F cell of pancreatic acinus

definition.val: An enteroendocrine cell commonest in the duodenum and jejunum, rare in ileum, that secretes cholecystokinin. This cell type is involved in the regulation of digestive enzymes and bile.
An enteroendocrine cell of duodenum and jejunum that produces gastric inhibitory peptide.

A enteroendocrine cell type that is numerous in ileum, present in jejunum and large intestine, few in duodenum. This cell type produces glucagon-like immunoreactants (glicentin, glucagon-37, glucagon-29, GLP-1 and -2) and PYY.
An enteroendorcine cell found in the ileum and jejunum that produces neurotensin.
Scattered in duodenojejunal mucosa, this enteroendocrine cell secretes secretin and serotonin.

An enteroendocrine cell which produces a gastrin- and cholecystokinin-like peptide. The apical microvilli-rich plasma membrane is in open contact with the small intestine mucosa. This cell type is devoid of gastrin-17 but contains other fragments of the gastrin polypeptide.
An epithelial cell of the mucosa associated with facial skeleton.
An enteroendorcine cell found in the fundus and pylorus, this cell type has dense round secretory granules that contain ghrelin.
A taste receptor cell that is characterized by morphologically identifiable synaptic contacts with the gustatory nerve fibers and expression of the synaptic membrane protein-25 (SNAP-25) and NCAM.
A taste receptor cell that has a short microvilli, a projecting apical region, a large rounded nucleus, and expresses taste chemoreceptors thus making them the transducing cell for taste qualities.

comments: There is debate about the exact lineage of these cell types from this progenitor. See PMID:15738192.

definition.val: A rounded, mitotically active stem cell which is the source of new cells of the taste bud; located basally.
A cell type that forms the boundary with the surrounding epithelium.

A densely staining taste receptor cell that contains many dense vacuoles in their apical regions which project into the apical space and bear microvilli. This cell type serves as a supporting cell by surrounding and isolating the other cell types from each other; secrete a dense amorphous material that surrounds the microvilli in the taste pore. This cell type expresses a glial glutumate transporter, GLAST.
A sperm bearing a Y chromosome. Chromosomal and genetic sex is established at fertilization in mammals and depends upon whether an X-bearing sperm or a Y-bearing sperm fertilizes the X-bearing ovum.
A sperm bearing an X chromosome. Chromosomal and genetic sex is established at fertilization in mammals and depends upon whether an X-bearing sperm or a Y-bearing sperm fertilizes the X-bearing ovum.

nodes.lbl: type I cell of carotid body

definition.val: A round or oval neuroepithelial cell that contacts other type I cells or capillaries. They occur in clusters that are surrounded by sheath cells (type-II cells) in the carotid body. This cell type is capable of secreting a number of neurotransmitters.

An epithelial cell of the thymus. Epithelial reticular cells are pleomorphic, stellate, non-phagocytic cells which seem to be supportive in function and are held together by desmosomes. They replace the fibroblastoid reticular cells found in other lymphoid organs. Other epithelial cells in the medulla have the ultrastructure of secretory cells. Although different epithelial cells throughout the thymus appear alike by light microscopy their ultrastructure and function varies.
An epithelial cell with a well defined Golgi apparatus that makes up the continuous layer of cells bordering the thymic tissue beneath the capsule.

A thymic epithelial cell that has an eccentric, round, or irregularly shaped hetero or euchromatic nucleus. The hallmark of this cell type is the presence of vacuoles, which are clustered in one area of the cytoplasm in the vicinity of the nucleus. The vacuoles are small and acquire a grape-like form, occasionally showing delicate internal microvillous projections.
An epithelial cell with high nuclear and cytoplasmic electron-density. This cell type is found in the deeper portions of the cortex but is more abundant in the medulla of the thymus.
A thymic epithelial cell with moderate nuclear and cytoplasmic electron-density. Scattered in the cortex, this cell type is predominant in the mid and deep cortex.

A thymic epithelial cell type with low nuclear and cytoplasmic electrondensity; has a round, euchromatic nucleus and occurs in small groups at the corticomedullary junction or scattered singly in the medulla.
An epithelial cell scattered in the cortex, predominant in the outer cortex with a large pale nucleus and a prominent nucleolus.

A small medullary thymic epithelial cell with a spindle shape, often arranged in groups and connected to each other by large desmosomes and interdigitations. The cytoplasm is sparse, with scanty organelles and thick bundles of cytokeratin.

synonyms.val: spindle shaped medullary thymic epithelial cell

definition.val: A synovial cell type that resembles fibroblasts, has abundant granular endoplasmic reticulum but contains fewer vacuoles and vesicles. This cell type secretes glycoproteins and hyaluronic acid.

A synovial cell that is macrophage-like, characterized by surface ruffles or lamellipodia, plasma membrane invaginations and associated micropinocytotic vesicles, Golgi apparatus and little granular endoplasmic reticulum.
A ciliated epithelial cell of the retina, this cell type uptakes sodium chloride and passes it to non-pigmented ciliary epithelial cells.
A multi-ciliated cell of the retina that lacks visual pigment and contributes to aqueous humor by secreting chloride ions. This cell type maintains gap junctions with pigmented epithelial cells.
An epithelial cell of the distal convoluted tubule of the kidney that helps regulate systemic levels of potassium, sodium, calcium, and pH.
An epithelial cell of the proximal tubule of the kidney.

nodes.lbl: brush border cell of the proximal tubule

definition.val: A brush border epithelial cell located in the proximal tubule of the kidney that detects fluid flow.
An epithelial cell of a skin gland.

synonyms.val: epithelial cell of gland of skin

definition.val: A basophil chromphil cell of the anterior pitiutary gland that produce adrenocorticotropic hormone, melanocyte-stimulating hormone and lipotropin. This cell type is irregular in shape and has short dendritic processes which are inserted among other neighboring cells;
An acidophil cell of the anterior pitiuatry gland that produces both prolactin and growth hormone.
An acidophilic cell of the anterior pituitary that produces prolactin.
An acidophilic cell of the anterior pituitary that produces growth hormone, somatotropin.
An ecto-epithelial cell of the prostate gland that secretes hormones.

nodes.lbl: external supporting cell of vestibular epithelium

definition.val: An auditory epithelial support cell located in the vestibular epithelium that has many hallmarks of glial cells. This cell type express glial markers such as vimentin, S100, glutamate-aspartate transporter, low affinity neurotrophin receptor p75, glial fibrillary acidic protein, and proteolipid protein.
An epithelial supporting cell located in the cochlea.
A supporting cell of the vestibular epithelium.

nodes.lbl: external limiting cell of vestibular epithelium

definition.val: An external limiting cell found in the vestibular epithelium.
A mesothelial cell capable of circulating in the blood by first losing its squamous character. This cell can incorporate into the regenerating mesothelium.
A cell that is part of the nervous system.
A cell of the supporting or framework tissue of the body, arising chiefly from the embryonic mesoderm and including adipose tissue, cartilage, and bone.
A cell of the embryo.

comments: This is an in vitro cell type and may be removed in future releases. These cells are reportedly SSEA-4-positive, CD73-negative, and CD324-positive.

definition.val: A stem cell of embryonic origin.

A cell of a fetus which is suspended in the amniotic fluid. Amniocytes are considered to arise from several tissues including fetal skin, the fetal urinary tract, umbilical cord, and the inner amniotic surface.

A myoepithelial cell that surrounds milk-secreting luminal epithelial cells. This cell type contracts under the stimulation of oxytocin and is attached to the basement membrane by hemidesmosomes and to the adjacent luminal cells by desmosomes. This cell type expresses high level of keratin-14 and is estrogen receptor alpha negative.
The milk-producing cell of the alveolar unit that emerges during pregnancy.

synonyms.val: luminal cell of alveolus of lactiferous gland

nodes.lbl: luminal epithelial cell of mammary gland

definition.val: A mammary epithelial cell that occurs in the lumen of the ductal and alveoli structure in the breast.
An epithelial cell of the mammary gland.
An epithelial cell of the bronchus.

nodes.lbl: basal epithelial cell of tracheobronchial tree

definition.val: An epithelial cell type that lacks the columnar shape typical for other respiratory epithelial cells. This cell type is able to differentiate into other respiratory epithelial cells in response to injury.
An undifferentiated columnar cell of the bronchus epithelium
A ciliated cell of the bronchus.
A fat cell derived from a neural crest cell.
An undifferentiated fibroblast that can be stimulated to form a fat cell.

A preadipocyte that is capable of differentiating into a brown adipocyte. This cell type expresses uncoupling protein-1, PPAR-gamma, PR-domain-containing 16; and PGC-1alpha (peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor-gamma (PPARgamma) coactivator-1alpha).
An endothelial cell that lines the oral cavitiy including the mucosa of the gums, the palate, the lip, and the cheek.
A stem cell located in the bulge of the hair follicle that can give rise to regenerate the new follicle with each hair cycle and to reepithelialize the epidermis during wound repair.

nodes.lbl: CD56-positive, CD161-positive immature natural killer cell, human

comments: Human markers; killer cell immunoglobulin-like receptor 2DL1 is used as a representative example (PRO at this time lacks a KIR superfamily).

definition.val: A natural killer cell that is developmentally immature, has the phenotype CD34-negative, CD56-positive, CD117-positive, CD122-positive,and CD161-positive.
A prostate epithelial cell that is CD133-positive, CD44-positive, integrin A2beta3-high. This cell is a stem cell for the prostate epithelium.
The exocrine cell of the prostate, this epithelial cell secretes prostatic acid phosphotase and PSA, and is dependent on androgen hormones for survival.
An undifferentiated cell of the prostate epithelium that lacks secretory activity.
A circulating endothelial cell of the phenotype CD146-positive, CD105-positive, CD45-negative. This cell type is indicative of recent vascular damage.

A natural killer cell subset that is found in the decidual of the uterus and is CD56-high, Galectin-1-positive and CD16-negative. This cell type represents the most abundant immune cell type in the decidual during the first trimester of pregnancy.

nodes.lbl: CD56-negative, CD161-positive immature natural killer cell, human

comments: Human markers; killer cell immunoglobulin-like receptor 2DL1 is used as a representative example (PRO at this time lacks a KIR superfamily).

definition.val: A natural killer cell that is developmentally immature, has the phenotype CD34-negative, CD56-negative, CD117-positive, CD122-positive,and CD161-positive.

nodes.lbl: CD27-low, CD11b-low immature natural killer cell, mouse

comments: Markers are associated with mouse cells.

definition.val: An immature natural killer cell that is NK1.1-positive, DX5-positive, Ly49-positive, CD27-low and CD11b-low. This cell type is found in high numbers in the liver.

nodes.lbl: Dx5-negative, NK1.1-positive immature natural killer cell, mouse

definition.val: An immature natural killer cell that is NK1.1-positive and DX-5 negative.

nodes.lbl: CD27-high, CD11b-high natural killer cell, mouse

definition.val: A mature natural killer cell that is CD27-high and CD11b-high. This cell type is capable of interferon-gamma secretion.

nodes.lbl: CD27-low, CD11b-high natural killer cell, mouse

definition.val: A CD27-low, CD11b-high natural killer cell that has a higher threshold of activation due to higher expression of inhibitory receptors.

nodes.lbl: CD27-high, CD11b-low natural killer cell, mouse

definition.val: A natural killer cell that is CD27-high and CD11b-low.

An endothelial cell that lines the intracavitary lumen of the heart, separating the circulating blood from the underlying myocardium. This cell type releases a number of vasoactive substances including prostacyclin, nitrous oxide and endothelin.
A multi-fate stem cell that is able to differentiate into the pancreas alpha, beta and delta endocrine cells. This cell type expresses neurogenin-3 and Isl-1.
A hematopoietic stem cell that exists during embryogenesis.

A hematopoietic stem cell that resides in the fetal liver. In mice, this cell type is first observed at E10.5. This cell type is MHC-positive, HSA-positive, AA4.1-positive, CD45-positive, Sca-1 positive, CD150-positive, CD48-negative and CD244-negative.
A hematopoietic stem found in the yolk sac. In mice, this cell type is Sca-1-negative, CD45-negative, MHC-negative, HSA-positive, AA4.1-positive, CD44-positive.

A large nucleated basophilic erythrocyte found in mammalian embryos. This cell type arises from the blood islands of yolk sacs and expresses different types of hemoglobins (beta-H1, gamma-1 and zeta) than adult erythrocytes. Considered a type of erythroblast as this cell type can enucleate in circulation.

A primitive erythrocyte that has undergone enucleation. This cell type is 3-6 fold bigger than the fetal derived erythrocytes that they co-circulate with during fetal development. Expresses epsilon-gamma hemoglobin chains.
A fetal liver derived enucleated erythrocyte. This erythrocyte resembles adult erythrocytes in that they are small (3- to 6- times smaller than primitive erythrocytes) and produce adult hemaglobins.
Derived from the Greek word pyren (the pit of a stone fruit), this is a transient nucleated cell type that results from exclusion of the nucleus from the primitive erythrocyte.
A hematopoietic stem cell of the placenta. This cell type is first observed E10.5 This cell type may give rise to fetal liver hematopoietic stem cells.
A hematopoietic stem cell from the aorta-gonad-mesonephros region of the developing embryo. First seen at E10.5 in mouse embryos. May give rise to fetal liver HSC.
A progenitor cell that is capable of forming colonies of primitive erythrocytes in the blood island of the yolk sac. First arrive at E7.5 in mouse and expresses CD41.

A cell located in the outermost proliferative zone of the external germinal layer that can differentiate into astroglial cells and granule cells. This cell type is glial fibrillary acidic protein-positive and NK1-positive.

A keratocyte is a specialized fibroblastÂ residing in the cornea stroma that has a flattened, dendritic cell located between the lamellae with a large flattened nucleus and lengthy processes which communicate with neighboring cells. ThisÂ cornealÂ layer, representing about 85-90% of corneal thickness, is built up from highly regular collagenous lamellae and extracellular matrix components. Keratocytes play the major role in keeping it transparent, healing its wounds, and synthesizing its components. This cell type secretes collagen I, V, VI, and keratin sulfate.
An epithelial cell of the cortical portion of the thymus. Epithelial cells in this region are required for positive selection of CD8-positive T cells.

An epithelial cell of the medullary thymus. This cell type expresses a diverse range of tissue-specific antigens. This promiscuous gene expression is a cell-autonomous property of medullary epithelial cells and is maintained during the entire period of thymic T cell output.
A smooth muscle cell of the myometrium that enlarges and stretches during pregnancy, and contracts in response to oxytocin.

A cell that lines the trabecular meshwork, which is an area of tissue in the eye located around the base of the cornea, near the ciliary body, and is responsible for draining the aqueous humor from the eye via the anterior chamber (the chamber on the front of the eye covered by the cornea). This cell may play a role in regulating intraocular pressure.
An endo-epithelial cell of the respiratory tract.

A differentiated form of a fungus produced during or as a result of an asexual or sexual reproductive process; usually a cell with a thick cell wall that stores and protects one or more nuclei. Spores may be produced in response to, and are characteristically resistant to, adverse environmental conditions.

A simple columnar epithelial cell that secretes mucin. Rough endoplasmic reticulum, mitochondria, the nucleus, and other organelles are concentrated in the basal portion. The apical plasma membrane projects microvilli to increase surface area for secretion.
A cell of an organism that does not pass on its genetic material to the organism's offspring (i.e. a non-germ line cell).
A transversely striated, synctial muscle cell, formed by the fusion of myoblasts.

nodes.lbl: growth hormone releasing hormone secreting cell

definition.val: A peptide hormone secreting cell that secretes growth hormone releasing hormone.
A hair cell of the ear that contains the organs of balance and hearing.

A giioblast cell that develops from a migratory neural crest cell. The SCP is embedded among neurons (axons) with minimal extracellular spaces separating them from nerve cell membranes and has no basal lamina. In rodents SCPs are the only cells in the Schwann cell linage that expresses Cdh19.

A glial cell that ensheaths multiple small diameter axons in the peripheral nervous system. The non-myelinating Schwann cell is embedded among neurons (axons) with minimal extracellular spaces separating them from nerve cell membranes and has a basal lamina. Cells can survive without an axon present. These cells can de-differentiate into immature Schwann cells.

A glial cell that develops from a Schwann cell precursor. The immature Schwann cell is embedded among neurons (axons) with minimal extracellular spaces separating them from nerve cell membranes and has a basal lamina. Cells can survive without an axon present. Immature Schwann cell can be found communally ensheathing large groups of axons.

comments: NOTE: currently variable immune gene segments are not represented in the OBO Foundry. Cross-product definitions were not made as a result. Also, there are three different nomenclatures for the variable gamma segments.

definition.val: A double negative thymocyte that has a T cell receptor consisting of a gamma chain containing a Vgamma2 segment, and a delta chain. This cell type is CD4-negative, CD8-negative and CD24-positive and is found in the fetal thymus.
A neurecto-epithelial cell found in the arachnoid villi of dura mater. This cell type facilitates flow of cerebrospinal fluid into the blood.
An asexual spore formed by Oomycetes; formed upon fertilization of an oosphere.
A conidium that has only one nucleus.
A conidium that has more than one nucleus.
A uninucleate spore formed on specialized cells or projections, sterigma, of a conidiophore head.
A macroconidium that has only one nucleus.
An oblong or round asexual spore formed from conidial chains.
A macroconidium that has more than one nucleus.
Cylindrical spore formed by development and compartmentation of hyphae; the hyphae are often supporting blastoconidiophores.
An arthroconidium that has more than one nucleus.
An arthroconidium that has only one nucleus.
A blastoconidium that has only one nucleus.
A blastoconidium that has more than one nucleus.

comments: replaced_by: PO:0025017

definition.val: Obsolete. Use PO:0025017 from Plant Ontology instead. A plant cell that arises through meiosis and develops into a gametophyte.
A monocyte that has characteristics of both patrolling and inflammatory monocytes.

comments: Markers are found in human cells. Normally they represent 3-5% of peripheral blood mDCs (human). These cells express high levels of CD283 (TLR3), are capable of producing IL-12p70 and IFN-beta upon stimulation, and inducing a TH1 response [PMCID:PMC2882828]. They are also Necl2-positive. May be human equivalent of murine CD8alpha-positive DCs.

definition.val: A myeloid dendritic cell found in the blood, lymph nodes, tonsil, bone marrow, and spleen that is CD141-positive (BDCA-3), XCR1-positive, and Clec9A-positive. This cell-type can cross-present antigen to CD8-positive T cells and can produce inteferon-beta.

comments: Markers are associated with mice. The Gr epitope is used to describe this cell type is found on both Ly6c and Ly6g. However, its the Ly6c that is considered the specific marker, and thus used in the cross-product.

definition.val: A resident monocyte that is Gr-1 high, CD43-negative, CX3CR1-negative, CD115-positive, and B220-negative.

comments: Markers are associated with human monocytes.

definition.val: A patrolling monocyte that is CD14-low and CD16-positive.

comments: This cell type is compatible with the HIPC Lyoplate markers for 'CD16+ monocyte'. Markers are associated with human cells. Note that this cell type encompasses both human intermediate monocytes (CD14+, CD16-low), and human non-classical monocytes (CD14-low, CD16+).

definition.val: A CD14-positive monocyte that is also CD16-positive and CCR2-negative.
An intermediate monocyte that is Gr1-positive, CD43-positive.

comments: Normally represent 10-20% of peripheral blood mDCs (human). They are also CD281-positive (TLR1), CD282-positive (TLR2), CD283-positive (TLR3), CD284-positive (TLR4), CD285-positive (TLR5), CD286-positive (TLR6), CD288-positive (TLR8), and CD290-positive (TLR10) [PMID:20204387]. Upon TLR stimulation, these cells were potent producers of CXCL8 (IL-8), while producing little TNF-alpha.

definition.val: A myeloid dendritic cell found in the blood that is CD1c-positive.
A precursor B cell that is AA4-positive, IgM-negative, CD19-positive, CD43-positive and HSA-positive.

nodes.lbl: mature dendritic epithelial T cell precursor

comments: NOTE: currently variable immune gene segments are not represented in the OBO Foundry. Cross-product definitions were not made as a result. Also, there are three different nomenclatures for the variable gamma segments.

definition.val: A thymocyte that has a T cell receptor consisting of a gamma chain that has as part a Vgamma3 segment, and a delta chain. This cell type is CD4-negative, CD8-negative and CD24-negative. This cell-type is found in the fetal thymus with highest numbers occurring at E17-E18.
A resting mature B cell within the Peyer's patch that is CD19-positive, B220-positive, IgM-positive, AA4-negative, CD23-positive, CD43-negative, and CD5-negative.

comments: NOTE: currently variable immune gene segments are not represented in the OBO Foundry. Cross-product definitions were not made as a result. Also, there are three different nomenclatures for the variable gamma segments.

definition.val: A thymocyte that has a T cell receptor consisting of a gamma chain containing Vgamma2 segment, and a delta chain. This cell type is CD4-negative, CD8-negative and CD24-negative. This cell-type is found in the fetal thymus.
A thymocyte found in the fetal thymus.
A post-natal thymocyte expressing components of the gamma-delta T cell receptor. This cell type is always double-negative (i.e. CD4-negative, CD8-negative).

comments: NOTE: currently variable immune gene segments are not represented in the OBO Foundry. Cross-product definitions were not made as a result. Also, there are three different nomenclatures for the variable gamma segments.

definition.val: A double negative post-natal thymocyte that has a T cell receptor consisting of a gamma chain containing a Vgamma2 segment, and a delta chain. This cell type is CD4-negative, CD8-negative and CD24-positive.

comments: NOTE: currently variable immune gene segments are not represented in the OBO Foundry. Cross-product definitions were not made as a result. Also, there are three different nomenclatures for the variable gamma segments.

definition.val: A thymocyte that has a T cell receptor consisting of a gamma chain containing Vgamma2 segment, and a delta chain. This cell type is CD4-negative, CD8-negative and CD24-negative.

comments: NOTE: currently variable immune gene segments are not represented in the OBO Foundry. Cross-product definitions were not made as a result. Also, there are three different nomenclatures for the variable gamma segments.

definition.val: A double negative post-natal thymocyte that has a T cell receptor consisting of a gamma chain that does not contain a Vgamma2 segment, and a delta chain. This cell type is CD4-negative, CD8-negative and CD24-positive.

comments: NOTE: currently variable immune gene segments are not represented in the OBO Foundry. Cross-product definitions were not made as a result. Also, there are three different nomenclatures for the variable gamma segments.

definition.val: A thymocyte that has a T cell receptor consisting of a gamma chain that does not contain the Vgamma2 segment, and a delta chain. This cell type is CD4-negative, CD8-negative and CD24-negative.

A cell that is found in the periacinar space of the exocrine pancreas and in perivascular and periductal regions of the pancreas, and has long cytoplasmic processes that encircle the base of the acinus. Expresses several intermediate filament proteins including vimentin and nestin. Shares many of the characteristics of hepatatic stellate cells, but not stellate cells of the central nervous system. Upon activation, this cell type undergoes morphological and gene expression changes that make the cell suggestive of being a type of myofibroblast.
A gamma-delta receptor that expresses Vgamma1.1 but does not express Vdelta6.3 chains in the T-cell receptor.
A gamma-delta receptor that expresses Vgamma1.1-Vdelta6.3 chains in the T-cell receptor.
A Vgamma1.1-positive, Vdelta6.3-negative thymocyte that is CD24-negative.
A Vgamma1.1-positive, Vdelta6.3-negative thymocyte that is CD24-positive.
A Vgamma1.1-positive, Vdelta6.3-positive thymocyte that is CD24-positive.
A Vgamma1.1-positive, Vdelta6.3-positive thymocyte that is CD24-negative.
An immature or mature cell of the first erythroid lineage to arise during embryonic development.
A pluripotent cell in the yolk sac that can give rise to mesenchymal cells including erythrocytes and endothelial cells.
A T cell that expresses a T cell receptor complex and has completed T cell selection.
A T cell that has not completed T cell selection.
A reticulocyte that retains the nucleus and other organelles. Found in birds, fish, amphibians and reptiles.
A reticulocyte lacking a nucleus and showing a basophilic reticulum under vital staining due to the presence of ribosomes.

comments: Observed in mice.

definition.val: A DN2 thymocyte that is Kit-hi.

comments: Observed in mice.

definition.val: A DN2 thymocyte that is Kit-low.

comments: ETPs are reportedly CD1a-negative, CD4-negative, CD7-positive, CD8a-negative, CD8b-negative, CD33-low, CD34-high, CD38-low, CD45RA-positive, and CD45RO-negative.

definition.val: A pro-T cell that is lin-negative, CD25-negative, CD127-negative, CD44-positive and kit-positive.

nodes.lbl: CD11b-positive, CD27-positive natural killer cell, mouse

comments: A natural killer cell that is NK1.1-positive, CD11b-positive, and CD27-positive.

definition.val: A mature natural killer cell that is CD11b-positive and CD27-positive.
A double-positive, alpha-beta thymocyte that is small and not proliferating.
A double-positive thymocyte that is large (i.e. has a high forward scatter signal in flow cytometry) and is actively proliferating.
A double-positive thymocyte that is CD69-positive and has begun positive selection.

A double-positive thymocyte that is undergoing positive selection, has high expression of the alpha-beta T cell receptor, is CD69-positive, and is in the process of down regulating the CD4 co-receptor.

A double-positive thymocyte that is undergoing positive selection, has high expression of the alpha-beta T cell receptor, is CD69-positive, and is in the process of down regulating the CD8 co-receptor.

comments: Described in the immgene database as being CD24-intermediate.

definition.val: A CD4-positive, CD8-negative thymocyte that is CD24-positive and expresses high levels of the alpha-beta T cell receptor.
A CD4-positive, CD8-negative thymocyte that expresses high levels of the alpha-beta T cell receptor and is CD69-positive.

comments: Described in the immgene database as being CD24-intermediate.

definition.val: A CD8-positive, CD4-negative thymocyte that is CD24-positive and expresses high levels of the alpha-beta T cell receptor.
A CD8-positive, CD4-negative thymocyte that expresses high levels of the alpha-beta T cell receptor and is CD69-positive.
A mature CD4-positive, CD8-negative alpha-beta T cell found in the thymus that is CD24-low and has high expression of the T cell receptor.
A mature CD8-positive, CD4-negative alpha-beta T cell found in the thymus that is CD24-low and has high expression of the T cell receptor.

comments: Note: Nk1.1 expression is restricted to C57BL strains of laboratory mice.

definition.val: A mature NK cell that is NK1.1-positive.
A NK1.1-positive T cell that is NKGA2-positive.
A NK1.1-positive T cell that is Ly49D-positive.
A NK1.1-positive T cell that is CD94-positive.

nodes.lbl: CD94-negative, Ly49CI-negative natural killer cell, mouse

definition.val: A NK1.1-positive T cell that is CD94-negative and Ly49Cl-negative.
A NK1.1-positive T cell that is Ly49Cl-positive.
A NK1.1-positive T cell that is Ly49H-positive.
A NK1.1-positive T cell that is Ly49D-negative.
A NK1.1-positive T cell that is Ly49Cl-negative.
A NK1.1-positive T cell that is CD94-negative.
A NK1.1-positive T cell that is Ly49H-negative.

nodes.lbl: CD94-positive Ly49CI-positive natural killer cell, mouse

definition.val: A NK1.1-positive T cell that is CD94-positive and Ly49Cl-positive.
A specialized hair cell that has an elongated kinocilium upon which an otolith accretes. The tether cell then anchors the otolith in place.

A multi-fate stem cell that is the source of cells for growth of the mammary gland during puberty and gestation. This cell type gives rise to both the luminal and myoepithelial cell types of the gland, and have been shown to have the ability to regenerate the entire organ in mice. This cell type also plays an important role in carcinogenesis of the breast. This cell type is Lin-, CD24-positive, CD29-hi.

The cell type from which oligodendrocytes develop. This cell originates from multiple structures within the developing brain including the medial ganglion eminence and the lateral ganglionic eminence. These cells migrate throughout the central nervous system and persist into adulthood where they play an important role in remyelination of injured neurons.
Cd4-negative, CD8_alpha-negative, CD11b-positive dendritic cell is a conventional dendritic cell that is CD11b-positive, CD4-negative, CD8_alpha-negative and is CD205-positive.
A CD11c-low plasmacytoid dendritic cell that is CD8alpha-negative and CD4-positive.
A CD11c-low plasmacytoid dendritic cell that is CD8alpha-positive and CD4-positive.
A Langerhans cell that is in the epidermis and is CD45-positive, MHCII-positive, and CD11b-positive.
A dermal dendritic cell that is langerin-positive and CD103-positive.
A dermal dendritic cell that is langerin-negative, CD103-negative, and CD11b-positive.
A conventional thymic dendritic cell that is CD8alpha-negative.
A conventional dendritic cell that is CD103-positive. This cell type is usually found in non-lymphoid tissue.
A F4/80-negative dendritic cell located in adipose tissue.
An adipose dendritic cell that is SIRPa-positive.
An adipose dendritic cell that is SIRPa-negative.
A conventional dendritic cell that expresses CD11b (ITGAM).
A CD11b-positive dendritic cell located in the serosal portion of the small intestine epithelium. This cell type is CD45-positive, MHC-II-positive, CD11c-low, CD103-negative.
A myeloid suppressor cell that is Gr1-high and CD11c-negative.
A myeloid suppressor cell that is Gr1-low and CD11c-positive.
Gr1-high monocyte that lacks MHC-II receptor complex.
Gr1-high monocyte that has a MHC-II receptor complex.
Gr1-low non-classical monocyte that lacks expression of a MHC-II complex.
Gr1-low non-classical monocyte that has low to intermediate expression of the MHC-II complex.
Gr1-low non-classical monocyte that has high surface expression of a MHC-II complex.
A MHC-II-negative classical monocyte located in lymphoid tissue that is F4/80-positive, CD11c-negative, and CD11b-high.
A MHC-II-negative classical monocyte located in lymphoid tissue that is F4/80-positive, CD11c-intermediate, and CD11b-high.
A tissue-resident macrophage located in the bone marrow. This cell type is B220-negative, CD3e-negative, Ly-6C-negative, CD115-positive, F4/80-positive.
A macrophage located in adipose tissue that is CD45-positive, CD11c-positive, and SIRPa-positive.
An adipose macrophage that does not express F4/80but is MHC-II-positive. This cell type exhibits autofluorescence under typical flow cyometry conditions.
An adipose macrophage that does not express MHC-II but is F4/80-positive.
A goblet cell located in the nasal epithelium.
The flattened smooth myoepithelial cells of mesodermal origin that lie just outside the basal lamina of the seminiferous tubule.
A melanocyte that produces pigment in the dermis.
A melanocyte that produces pigment within the hair follicle.

comments: The text defintion reference to the MP term appears to reference an epidermal melanocyte term. This term represents any melanocyte in any epithelium.

definition.val: A melanocyte that produces pigment in the epithelium.
A melanocyte of the retina. This cell type is distinct from pigmented retinal epithelium.

A melanocyte located between the epithelial marginal cell layer and the mesodermal basal cell layer within the intrastrial space; the predominant cellular component of the electrogenic machinery that generates an endocochlear potential (80-100 mV) .
A neuronal receptor that respond to mechanical pressure or distortion in the skin.

A trophoblast cell that has a large volume of cytoplasm, is polyploid and is usually mononuclear but is also occasionally multi-nucleate. This cell type is important in establishing maternal physiology and remodeling of the vasculature of the placenta.

Any muscle cell in which the fibers are not organised into sarcomeres.
Any hematopoietic cell that is a precursor of some other hematopoietic cell type.
A transversely striated, synctial cell of skeletal muscle. It is formed when proliferating myoblasts exit the cell cycle, differentiate and fuse.
A myotube that is part of some somatic muscle.  Examples include arthropod somatic muscle cells.
A muscle cell that is part of some somatic muscle.
A somatic muscle cell that is oblquely striated.  Examples include the somatic muscles of nematodes.

A myoblast that detemines the properties (size, shape and attachment to the epidermis) of a `somatic muscle myotube` (CL:0008003) .  It develops into a somatic muscle myotube via fusion with `fusion component myoblasts` (CL:0000621).
A muscle cell that is part of some visceral muscle
A visceral muscle cell that is striated.  Examples include the visceral muscle cells of arhtropods.
A visceral muscle that is transversely striated.  Examples include the visceral muscle cells of arthropods.
A cranial motor neuron whose soma is located in the midbrain andor hindbrain and which innervates the skeletal muscles of the eye or tongue.

A skeletal muscle satellite cell that divides by stem cell division.  A proportion of this population undergoes symmetric stem cell division, producing two skeletal muscle satellite stem cells. The rest undergo asymmetric stem cell division - retaining their identity while budding off a daughter cell that differentiates into an adult skeletal muscle myoblast.

A skeletal muscle satellite cell that is mitotically quiescent.  These cells are wedge shaped and have a large nuclear to cytoplasmic ratio with few organelles, a small nucleus and condensed interphase chromatin. Satellite cells typically remain in this state until activated following muscle damage.
A visceromotor motor neuron whose soma is located in the hindbrain, and which synapses to parasympathetic neurons that innervate tear glands, sweat glands, and the smooth muscles of the head.

comments: In vertebrates, all motor neurons are excitatory, but various types of inhibitory motor neurons exist in invertebrates.

definition.val: A motor neuron that is capable of directly inducing muscle contraction.

comments: In vertebrates, all motor neurons are excitatory, but various types of inhibitory motor neurons exist in invertebrates.

definition.val: A motor neuron that is capable of directly inhibiting muscle contraction.
A skeletal muscle cell that has become mitotically active - typically following muscle damage.

comments: The vast majority of these cells develop from skeletal muscle satellite cells, although there are some reports of other origins.

definition.val: A skeletal muscle myoblast that is part of a skeletal mucle.  These cells are formed following acivation and division of skeletal muscle satellite cells. They form a transient population that is lost when they fuse to form skeletal muscle fibers.
A myoblast that is commited to developing into a somatic muscle.
A non-polarised cell precursor cell that is part of some mesenchyme, is associated with the cell matrix but is not connected to other cells and is capable of migration.
A skeletal muscle satellite cell that undergoes symmetric division to produce two adult skeleltal muscle myoblasts.

A mesenchymal cell of the endocardial cushion.   These cells develop via an epithelial to mesenchymal transition when endocardial cells break cell-to-cell contacts and migrate into the cardiac jelly. Cells from this population form the heart septa and valves.

comments: Duplicate term.

definition.val: An endocrine cell that is part of the pancreas.
A neuron that release noradrenaline (noriphinephrine) as a neurotransmitter.
An epithelial cell that is part of the epithelium of a tracheal tube in an open tracheal system, such as that found in insects.

A bipolar neuron found in the retina that is synapsed by rod photoreceptor cells.  These neurons have axons that arborize and synapse to targets in inner plexiform layers 4 and 5 and depolarize in response to light.
A pericyte of the decidual vasculature.
Mural cells are pericytes and the vascular smooth muscle cells (vSMCs) of the microcirculation.
A trophoblast cell that is not part of a placental villous.

A lower motor neuron that innervates only intrafusal muscle fibers. Unlike the alpha motor neurons, gamma motor neurons do not directly adjust the lengthening or shortening of muscles but function in adjusting the sensitivity of muscle spindles and in keeping muscle spindles taut, thereby allowing the continued firing of alpha neurons.

A large, multipolar lower motor neuron of the brainstem and spinal cord that innervates the extrafusal muscle fibers of skeletal muscle and are directly responsible for initiating their contraction. While their cell bodies are in the CNS (in the anterior gray horn of the spinal cord), they are part of the somatic nervous system - a branch of the PNS.
The motor neurons of vertebrates that directly innervate skeletal muscles. They receive input from upper motor neurons.

A skeletal muscle fiber that is innervated by alpha motor neuron and generates tension by contracting, thereby allowing for skeletal movement. These fibers make up the large mass of skeletal muscle tissue and are attached to bones by tendons.

A skeletal muscle fiber that is part of a muscle spindle. These are specialized muscle fibers that serve as proprioceptors, detecting the amount and rate of change in length of a muscle. They are innervated by both sensory neurons and motor neurons (gamma and beta motorneurons, collectively referred to as fusimotor neurons).

A glutamatergic motor neuron with a soma in the brainstem or cerebral cortex.  They do not synapse directly to muscles but rather to lower motor neurons, which do.  They are the main controllers of voluntary movement.

A giant pyramidal neuron with a soma in layer Vb of the primary motor cortex that sends its axons down the spinal cord via the corticospinal tract, either synapsing directly with alpha motor neurons, or targeting interneurons in the spinal cord. In humans, Betz cells are the largest known in the central nervous system.
A sensory neuron of the spinal nerve that senses body position and sends information about how much the muscle is stretched to the spinal cord.
Any cell in the compound eye, a light sensing organ composed of ommatidia.
Any cell participating in the inflammatory response to a foreign substance, e.g. neutrophil, macrophage.
Any cell in the midgut (middle subdivision of a digestive tract) of a larva.
Any cell in the retina, the innermost layer or coating at the back of the eyeball, which is sensitive to light and in which the optic nerve terminates.
Any cell in a salivary gland.

definition.val: A rapidly proliferating population of cells that differentiate from stem cells of the intestinal crypt of the large intestine. Stem cells located in the crypts of Lieberkühn give rise to proliferating progenitor or transit amplifying cells that differentiate into the four major epithelial cell types. These include columnar absorptive cells or enterocytes, mucous secreting goblet cells, enteroendocrine cells and paneth cells.

A follicular dendritic cell located in the Peyer's patch. These cells from a meshwork in which Peyer's patch B cells reside.

definition.val: A highly specialized cell type exclusive to and forming neuroepithelium of the Saccus vasculosus, covering the caudal diverticulum of the infundibular recess.

A cell with a flagellum surrounded by a collar of microvilli. The motion of the flagellum draws water past the microvilli, serving either a feeding or sensory function. Collar cells are found in multiple animals, including sponges, echinoderms, and cnidarians. They are also found outside animals in the choanoflagellates. Although collar cells are superficially similar, their cytoskeletal structure and functional biology are different in different groups of organisms.
A zygote in a plant or an animal.
A CNS interneuron located in the dorsal horn of the spinal cord.
A motor neuron that passes from the spinal cord toward or to a muscle and conducts an impulse that causes movement.

definition.val: A motor neuron that is generated only on limb levels and send axons into the limb mesenchyme.

A neurosecretory neuron residing mainly in the hypothalamic supraoptic and paraventricular nuclei and in a number of smaller accessory cell groups between these two nuclei, that secretes the hormones oxytocin and vasopressin.
A vetebrate lens cell that is any of the elongated, tightly packed cells that make up the bulk of the mature lens in a camera-type eye.

definition.val: An interneuron that uses GABA as a vesicular neurotransmitter.  These interneurons are inhibitory

A cell in the area of mesoderm in the neurulating embryo that flanks and forms simultaneously with the neural tube. The cells of this region give rise to somites.
A hemocyte derived from head mesoderm, which enters the hemolymph as acirculating cell.
A plasmatocyte derived from head mesoderm.
A cell derived from the mesoderm that is found at the periphery of the embryo.
A cell derived from the mesoderm that is located between the paraxial mesoderm and the lateral plate.

A cell of the neural crest. Neural crest cells are multipotent. Premigratory neural crest cells are found at the neural plate boarder, some of which will undergo ectomesynchymal transition and delamination to form migratory neural crest cells.
A sperm cell that is cabaple of motion (motility).
A sperm cell that is not cabaple of motion (motility).
A motile sperm cell that contain no F-actin, and their motility is powered by a dynamic filament system.
A motile sperm cell that contains a slender threadlike microscopic appendage that enables motion.

Cell that is part of the vagal neural crest population. The vagal neural crest arises from the axial level of somites 1-7 and has been described as a hybrid between the head and the trunk populations.

A group 3 innate lymphoid cell that express ROR gamma t and IL-7R alpha in the absence of lineage markers (e.g. CD3, CD19, B220, CD11c, Gr-1), with the functional ability to interact with mesenchymal cells through lymphotoxin and tumor necrosis factor. Lymphoid tissue-inducer cells are key to the development of lymph nodes and Peyer’s patches.
A mesothelial cell that is part of the epicardium.
An undifferentiated cell that originates from a neural stem cell and has the capacity to generate multiple types of lineage-restricted progenitors but not to self-renew.
A fibroblast that is part of upper back skin.
A fibroblast that is part of skin of back.

A double negative thymocyte that is CD3-positive, CD4-negative, CD8-negative, that that are present in the periphery in very low numbers and predominantly produce INF-gamma, TNF-alpha, and a low amount of TGF-beta, but not IL-2, IL-4, IL-10 or IL-13 upon activation.

synonyms.val: CD4-negative, CD8-negative, alpha-beta regulatory T cells
An effector T cell that displays impaired effector functions (e.g., rapid production of effector cytokines, cytotoxicity) and has limited proliferative potential.

definition.val: A precursor cell that has a tendency to differentiate into a specific type of cell. They are descendants of stem cells, only they are more constrained in their differentiation potential or capacity for self-renewal, and are often more limited in both senses.

synonyms.val: A neural-crest derived glial cell that supports the growth and survival of primary olfactory neuroons from the neuroepithelium in the nasal cavity to the brain by encasing large bundles of numerous unmyelinated axons.

Parasympathetic neurons are part of the parasympathetic nervous sysem and the cell bodies lie in the brain and sacral region of the spinal cord. The neurons are mainly cholinergic.
Sympathetic neurons are part of the sympathetic nervous system and are primarily adrenergic producing the neurotransmitter noradrenalin along with other neuropeptides.
